It is important to distinguish between two different paths, as "Docker repository" can mean two things here. Choose the one that matches your goal:

ğŸ“‚ The Source Code: Uploading your files (like Dockerfile, .py, .js) so others can read the code.

ğŸ“¦ The Docker Image: Uploading the built, runnable container to the GitHub Container Registry (GHCR) so others can run it.

ğŸ“‚ Part 1: Uploading Source Code (The Blueprint)
This is the standard way to share work. You are simply pushing code to a GitHub repository.

ğŸ› ï¸ Prerequisites
You have git installed.

You have a GitHub account.

ğŸ‘£ Steps
1. ğŸ Initialize Git Go to your project folder in your terminal:

Bash
git init
2. ğŸ™ˆ Create a .gitignore Ensure you don't upload junk files. Create a file named .gitignore and add:

Plaintext
node_modules/
__pycache__/
.env
.DS_Store
3. ğŸ“¸ Commit your code Save the current state of your project:

Bash
